Method chaining strikes again. You can read [here][1] of _why_ the designers of this feature found it complicated to implement (it has to do with the fact that lambda&#39;s/method references are _poly expressions_ - their types are context dependent). Such a feature would require some extra burden on the compiler - and while your example would be a fairly trivial example to solve, `javac` has to care about a lot more than triviality; thus this is not yet implemented, even in java-12. 

The easiest solution IMO, since this has to do with method chaining (and in your case this is possible), is not to chain:

    Optional&lt;Class&lt;?&gt;&gt; first = Optional.empty().map(o -&gt; getStringClass(o));
    Class&lt;?&gt; second = first.orElse(String.class);


  [1]: http://cr.openjdk.java.net/~dlsmith/jsr335-0.6.1/D.html

